 form, history, lineation, and narrative in Blake’s work, establishing contact with major topics in Gothic studies. Then refines its focus to Blake’s bloody, nervous bodies, through which he explores various kinds of Gothic horror related to reproduction, anatomy, sexuality, affect, and materiality. Rather than transcendent images, this collection attends to Blake’s ‘dark visions of torment’.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGothic poetry (Literary genre), EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aGothic revival (Literature)zGreat BritainxHistory. 4aGothic 2018. 4aGothic 2019. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBlake.  aGothic.  aHorror.  aRomanticism.  aart history.  aembodiment.  amediation.  amyth.  aterror.1 aBaulch, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBundock, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBundock, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCodsi, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCogan, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColebrook, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Tristanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEffinger, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEffinger, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGonzález-Treviño, Ana Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLussier, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtto, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaub, Kiel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1